TY  - JOUR
T1  - Advertising Cost Interactions and the Optimality of Pulsing
AU  - Hahn, Minhi
AU  - Hyun, Jin-Sok
Y1  - 1991/02/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.37.2.157
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.37.2.157
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 157
EP  - 169
VL  - 37
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Whether pulsing, other than chattering, can be optimal is an important concern to both advertising practitioners and marketing scientists. In this paper, we explicitly incorporate various types of costs to a one-state advertising model to analyze the effect of these costs on the optimal advertising policy. We prove that the interaction of fixed and pulsing costs does make pulsing optimal under a reasonable condition. This result not only identifies an important factor that leads to the optimality of pulsing, but also generalizes the finding obtained by Sasieni (1971).
AB  - Whether pulsing, other than chattering, can be optimal is an important concern to both advertising practitioners and marketing scientists. In this paper, we explicitly incorporate various types of costs to a one-state advertising model to analyze the effect of these costs on the optimal advertising policy. We prove that the interaction of fixed and pulsing costs does make pulsing optimal under a reasonable condition. This result not only identifies an important factor that leads to the optimality of pulsing, but also generalizes the finding obtained by Sasieni (1971).
